Using the  identity 
\begin{eqnarray} \label{identity}
&\,&\frac{2}{\pi (\nu-1)!^2}\,\sum_{l \in \mathbb{Z}} \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{(n+\nu)!}{n!} \frac{(n+r|l|+\nu)!}{(n+r|l|)!} \times {\mathrm{e}}^{-i(1+\nu+2n)t -i|l|r t +i l r \vartheta}\\
&=& \frac{\nu^2}{2^{\nu} r\ \pi}\sum_{k=0}^{r-1} \left(\frac{1}{\cos t- \cos \left(\vartheta+2\pi \frac{k}{r}\right)}\right)^{\nu+1}\,.{\nonumber}
\end{eqnarray}
we get for arbitrary integer $\Delta>1$
\begin{eqnarray}\label{images}
\left< \mathcal{O}_{\Delta}(t, \vartheta) \mathcal{O}_{\Delta}(0, 0) \right> &=&
 \frac{2(\Delta-1)^2}{ \pi\,r}\sum_{k=0}^{r-1} \left(\frac{1}{2(\cos t- \cos \left(\vartheta+2\pi \frac{k}{r}\right))}\right)^{\Delta}\,. 
\end{eqnarray}
For the special case $\Delta=1$ one can analogously obtain
\begin{eqnarray}\label{images1}
\left< \mathcal{O}_1(t, \vartheta) \mathcal{O}_1(0, 0) \right> &=&
 \frac{1}{\pi r}\,\sum_{k=0}^{r-1} \,\frac{1}{\cos t- \cos \left(\vartheta+2\pi \frac{k}{r}\right)}\,.
 \end{eqnarray}

To prove (\ref{identity}), consider the sum over $l$:
\begin{eqnarray} 
&&\sum_{l \in \mathbb{Z}} \frac{(n+r|l|+\nu)!}{(n+r|l|)!} \times {\mathrm{e}}^{-i|l|r t +i l r \vartheta}\\{\nonumber} &=&  \sum_{l=-\infty}^{\infty}  \frac{(n+r|l|+\nu)!}{(n+r|l|)!} \frac{1}{r} \sum_{p=0}^{r-1} {\mathrm{e}}^{-i|l|r t +i r l \left(\vartheta+\frac{2\pi p}{r}\right)} \\& = & \sum_{l=-\infty}^{\infty}  \frac{(n+|l|+\nu)!}{(n+|l|)!} \frac{1}{r} \sum_{p=0}^{r-1} {\mathrm{e}}^{-i|l| t +i  l \left(\vartheta+\frac{2\pi p}{r}\right)}{\nonumber} \\&-& \sum_{q=1}^{r-1}  \sum_{l=-\infty}^{\infty}  \frac{(n+r|l|+q+\nu)!}{(n+r|l|+q)!} \frac{1}{r} \sum_{p=0}^{r-1} {\mathrm{e}}^{-i(|l|r+q) t +i (r l+q) \left(\vartheta+\frac{2\pi p}{r}\right)}{\nonumber}
\end{eqnarray}
The summation over $p$ in the last term can be conducted:
\begin{eqnarray}
&&\sum_{p=0}^{r-1} {\mathrm{e}}^{\frac{2\pi p q}{r}} {\mathrm{e}}^{2\pi l p} = \sum_{p=0}^{r-1} {\mathrm{e}}^{\frac{2\pi p q}{r}} = \frac{1-{\mathrm{e}}^{2\pi i q }}{1-{\mathrm{e}}^{\frac{2 \pi i q}{r}}} = 0 \quad \forall q  \label{sumq}\,;
\end{eqnarray}
Therefore, the entire $q$-sum vanishes, and we have 
\begin{eqnarray}
&\,&\left< \mathcal{O}_{1+\nu}(t, \vartheta) \mathcal{O}_{1+\nu}(0, 0) \right> =\\&=&{\nonumber} \frac{1}{r} \sum_{k=0}^{r-1}\frac{2}{\pi (\nu-1)!^2}\sum_{l \in \mathbb{Z}} \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{(n+\nu)!}{n!} \frac{(n+|l|+\nu)!}{(n+|l|)!} \times {\mathrm{e}}^{-i(1+\nu+2n)t -i|l| t}{\mathrm{e}}^{i l \left(\vartheta+\frac{2\pi k}{r}\right)} \,,
\end{eqnarray}
which, in analogy to the empty AdS result (\ref{corseries}), is precisely the sum over images (\ref{images}). 
A particular case of the formula (\ref{images}) was obtained in \cite{Bal05} in case of a massless scalar field (i. e. $\Delta=2$) by using the images prescription for the bulk-boundary propagator itself. 

The renormalized images prescription in the geodesic approximation \cite{AAT,AA}, generally speaking, is formulated for arbitrary $\Delta$ for the piece of correlator which doesn't carry information about the causal structure - for example, in empty AdS case that would be the factor before the exponential in (\ref{Wightmann}), that is the absolute value of geodesic legth in the power of $\Delta$. This geodesic correlator has the reflection symmetry \cite{Arefeva2015,AAT}. Keeping this in mind, one can formulate the geodesic images prescription for the entire correlator, taking into account its causal structure. As seen in (\ref{Gads}), in the case of integer $\Delta$, which is what we consider in our scalar field prescription, the expressions for correlation functions are significantly simplified.

